dataDictionary.Title: PDS4 Data Dictionary
dataDictionary.Description: This document is a dump of the contents of the PDS4 Data Dictionary

class.title: ISS
class.description: Attributes relevant to the Voyager Imaging Science Subsystem (ISS) instrument and its observations.

class.title: ISS_Legacy_Label
class.description: Attributes relevant to the Voyager Imaging Science Subsystem (ISS) instrument and its observations that are taken from the legacy label and are not otherwise attributed. These attributes are being retained for historical documentation purposes. Nothing in this class should be required for normal processing or analysis of Voyager ISS images.

class.title: Voyager
class.description: Elements relevant to the Voyager 1 and/or Voyager 2 spacecraft mission.

class.title: Voyager_Telemetry
class.description: Container for elements describing the process of transferring Voyager data from the spacecraft to Earth.

class.title: Voyager_Timing
class.description: Container for elements describing the time at which a data product was obtained

attribute.title: earth_received_time
attribute.description: Time at which the image was received at Earth. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword EARTH_RECEIVED_TIME

attribute.title: edit_mode_id
attribute.description: Edit mode of the camera, indicates amount of data read from the vidicon. '1:1' indicates the full-resolution of the vidicon. Other values include '3:4', '1:2', '1:3', '1:5', and '1:10'. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword EDIT_MODE_ID

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: Vidicon readout was at full resolution.
Vidicon readout was at one-tenth resolution.
Vidicon readout was at one-half resolution.
Vidicon readout was at one-third resolution.
Vidicon readout was at one-fifth resolution.
Vidicon readout was at three-quarters resolution.

attribute.title: exposure_duration
attribute.description: Time period during which the shutter was open Source Data Product Origin: Keyword EXPOSURE_DURATION
attribute.unitId: day, hr, julian day, microseconds, min, ms, ns, s, yr

attribute.title: filter_name
attribute.description: Optical filter used for the image. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword FILTER_NAME

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: NAC Filter #2 or WAC Filter #1, spanning portions of the Visible spectrum from 0.43 to 0.53 microns
WAC Filter #0, spanning portions of the Visible spectrum from 0.614 to 0.624 microns. Also called CH4_JS or METHANE-JST.
WAC Filter #6, spanning portions of the Visible spectrum from 0.536 to 0.546 microns. Also called CH4_U or METHANE-U.
NAC Filter #0 or #4 or WAC Filter #2, spanning portions of the Visible and Ultraviolet spectrum from 0.28 to 0.64 microns
NAC Filter #5 or #6 or WAC Filter #5, spanning portions of the Visible spectrum from 0.53 to 0.64 microns
NAC Filter #3 or WAC Filter #7, spanning portions of the Visible spectrum from 0.59 to 0.64 microns
WAC Filter #0, spanning portions of the Visible spectrum from 0.588 to 0.590 microns. Also called NAD or SODIUM-D.
NAC Filter #7, spanning portions of the Ultraviolet spectrum from 0.28 to 0.37 microns
NAC Filter #1 or WAC Filter #3, spanning portions of the Visible and Ultraviolet spectrum from 0.35 to 0.45 microns

attribute.title: filter_number
attribute.description: Optical filter identification number, contains the unique number associated with the optical filter for the image. This value should correspond with that given in the definition of this label's value of filter_name. Despite the redundancy, it is retained here as it was in the source product label, for historical purposes. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword FILTER_NUMBER

attribute.title: gain_mode_id
attribute.description: The gain state of an instrument. Gain is a constant value, set by the observer, that indicates the approximate number of photon-excited electrons registered by the detector that correlate to one "data number" (DN). Source Data Product Origin: Keyword GAIN_MODE_ID

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: The higher of the two gain states for Voyager ISS
The lower of the two gain states for Voyager ISS

attribute.title: image_id
attribute.description: Image identification, takes the form: nnnnes+ddd, where 'nnnn' = picture sequence number for a given day, 'e' = planet of encounter (J=Jupiter, S=Saturn, U=Uranus, N=Neptune), 's' = Voyager spacecraft (1 or 2), - sign indicates before and a + sign indicates after closest planetary approach. 'ddd' = number of days from closest approach. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword IMAGE_ID

attribute.title: image_number
attribute.description: Flight Data Subsystem (FDS) clock count at time of image acquisition. There is a unique IMAGE_NUMBER for each image in a planetary encounter. The clock count is always a seven digit value, five digits to the left of the decimal point and two digits to the right of the decimal point. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword IMAGE_NUMBER

attribute.title: pds_source_product_data_anomaly_type
attribute.description: Data recording anomalies in the image. This attribute, while required, is nillable. A nil_reason of missing indicates that it was missing from the source product, which in turn implies no anomalies were detected. In the source product, DATA_ANOMALY_TYPE = RAM_DATA_CORRUPTION indicates that spurious values exist in the image data due to corruption of the random access memory onboard the spacecraft. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword DATA_ANOMALY_TYPE

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: Spurious values exist in the image data due to corruption of the random access memory onboard the spacecraft.

attribute.title: pds_source_product_description
attribute.description: A description of the image, as recorded in the original source product label. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword DESCRIPTION

attribute.title: pds_source_product_note
attribute.description: The observational intent of the image, as recorded in the original source product label. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword NOTE

attribute.title: pds_source_product_target_name
attribute.description: The value of TARGET_NAME as given in the source product label. The relationship between this value and the actual intentions of the observer is unknown. The most accurate, though potentially flawed identification of the intended target is given in the Target_Identification class elsewhere in the label. This attribute is included in the PDS4 label for historical reasons. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword TARGET_NAME

attribute.title: scan_mode_id
attribute.description: Scan rate of vidicon readout. The instrument scan rate affects the radiometric properties of the camera because of the dark current buildup on the vidicon. Values can be '1:1', '2:1', '3:1', '5:1', and '10:1'. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword SCAN_MODE_ID

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: Vidicon readout was at one-tenth speed.
Vidicon readout was at full speed.
Vidicon readout was at one-half speed.
Vidicon readout was at one-third speed.
Vidicon readout was at one-fifth speed.

attribute.title: shutter_mode_id
attribute.description: Shutter mode. Indicates which camera was shuttered, Narrow Angle and/or Wide Angle. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword SHUTTER_MODE_ID

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: Shutter remained closed for Narrow Angle and Wide Angle cameras.
Both the Narrow Angle and the Wide Angle shutters opened simultaneously
Only the Narrow Angle shutter opened
Neither the Narrow Angle nor the Wide Angle shutter opened
Only the Wide Angle shutter opened

attribute.title: legacy_label_compression_state
attribute.description: Whether the image compression mode was operating.

attribute.title: legacy_label_lsb_truncate
attribute.description: Whether the LSB Truncation mode was operating. In this mode, only a certain number of the least significant bits are kept, while the bits corresponding to larger place values are truncated.

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: @@@ I'm not sure what this would mean. @@@
The LSB Truncate mode was off
The LSB Truncate mode was on

attribute.title: legacy_label_VICAR1
attribute.description: The "VICAR-1" label that was originally attached to the image. Information on how to decode this text can be found at @@@@@@. To the extent possible, the information is captured in the attached VICAR-2 header and/or the PDS4 XML label. This VICAR-1 legacy label is being retained for historical documentation purposes, and in case there is any question about how the rest of the label items were derived. Contemporaneous Voyager documentation sometimes refers to these legacy labels.

attribute.title: mission_phase_name
attribute.description: Time period within the Voyager 1 or Voyager 2 mission, as defined by the mission team. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword MISSION_PHASE_NAME

PermissibleValue.valueMeaning: The period of cruise from Earth to Jupiter. For Voyager 1 this is 1977-09-06T00:00 to 1979-01-06T12:00. For Voyager 2 this is 1977-08-20T00:00 to 1979-04-25T12:00.
The period from the final planetary encounter to the end of the mission. For Voyager 1 this is 1980-12-14T12:00 to End of Mission. For Voyager 2 this is 1989-10-02T12:00 to End of Mission.
The period surrounding the Jupiter Encounter. For Voyager 1 this is 1979-01-06T12:00 to 1979-04-13T12:00. For Voyager 2 this is 1979-04-25T12:00 to 1979-08-05T12:00.
The period of cruise from Jupiter to Saturn. For Voyager 1 this is 1979-04-13T12:00 to 1980-08-22T12:00. For Voyager 2 this is 1979-08-05T12:00 to 1981-06-05T12:00.
The day of launch. For Voyager 1 this is 1977-09-05. For Voyager 2 this is 1977-08-20.
The period surrounding the Neptune Encounter. This does not apply to Voyager 1. For Voyager 2 this is 1989-06-05T12:00 to 1989-10-02T12:00.
The period surrounding the Saturn Encounter. For Voyager 1 this is 1980-08-22T12:00 to 1980-12-14T12:00. For Voyager 2 this is 1981-06-05T12:00 to 1981-09-25T12:00.
The period of cruise from Saturn to Uranus. This does not apply to Voyager 1. For Voyager 2 this is 1981-09-25T12:00 to 1985-11-04T12:00
The period surrounding the Uranus Encounter. This does not apply to Voyager 1. For Voyager 2 this is 1985-11-04T12:00 to 1986-02-25T12:00.
The period of cruise from Uranus to Neptune. This does not apply to Voyager 1. For Voyager 2 this is 1986-02-25T12:00 to 1989-06-05T12:00.

attribute.title: spacecraft_clock_count_partition
attribute.description: The Voyager spacecraft clock, known as the Flight Data System (FDS), was reset to zero multiple times, dividing each mission into FDS partitions. This attribute signifies which FDS partition was in effect for this data product.

attribute.title: spacecraft_clock_start_count
attribute.description: The spacecraft clock value at the beginning of a time period of interest. Voyager used the term Flight Data System (FDS) for this quantity, which is equivalent to the term spacecraft clock (SCLK) more commonly used by subsequent missions. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword SPACECRAFT_CLOCK_START_COUNT

attribute.title: spacecraft_clock_stop_count
attribute.description: The spacecraft clock value at the end of a time period of interest. Voyager used the term Flight Data System (FDS) for this quantity, which is equivalent to the term spacecraft clock (SCLK) more commonly used by subsequent missions. Source Data Product Origin: Keyword SPACECRAFT_CLOCK_STOP_COUNT
